    "answer": "Here is my analysis and proposed solution options:\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nThe problem is that `SubagentTimeoutMilliseconds` defaults to **0** (disabled) in `RelayConfigLoader.Defaults()` (line 27), so no absolute ceiling is imposed on any stage attempt. An agent that is CPU-active and producing output but making no real progress (flailing) can run unbounded. The fix requires: (1) a non-zero default ceiling, and (2) scaling that ceiling by `TurnBoostMultiplier` (10\u00d7) for tasks in `BoostTurnsTaskIds`, so a legitimately long-running boosted task isn't falsely reaped.\n\n### Key code locations\n\n| Concern | File | Lines |\n|---|---|---|\n| Default ceiling = 0 | `RelayConfigLoader.cs` | 27, 210 |\n| Ceiling consumed | `ProcessRunners.RunAsync.cs` | 40\u201341, 85, 102\u2013104 |\n| Boost turns computed (no ceiling scaling) | `RelayDriver.VerifyFix.cs` | 216\u2013218 |\n| `AbsoluteCeilingMs` field | `ActivityWatchdog` | 39, 77, 84, 176 |\n| `StageInvocation` (no ceiling field yet) | `StageInvocation.cs` | (entire file) |\n\n---\n\n## Solution options\n\n### Option A \u2014 Thread scaled ceiling through a new `StageInvocation` field\n\n**Change the default** in `RelayConfigLoader.Defaults()` from 0 to a computed non-zero value, e.g. `MaxTurns * 60_000` (200 \u00d7 60 s = 3.3 h). **Add an `AbsoluteCeilingMs` field** to `StageInvocation`. **In `BuildInvocation`**, apply boost scaling: if the task is boosted, multiply the ceiling by `TurnBoostMultiplier`. **In `RunAsync`**, read `invocation.AbsoluteCeilingMs` instead of `_config.SubagentTimeoutMilliseconds`.\n\n**Files touched:** `RelayConfigLoader.cs`, `StageInvocation.cs`, `RelayDriver.VerifyFix.cs`, `ProcessRunners.RunAsync.cs`, test files.\n\n**Pros:** Explicit, testable at the invocation layer; boost scaling is co-located with turn boost logic; no guessing about per-turn time in `RunAsync`.\n\n**Cons:** Adds a new field to a record used across the domain boundary; all test call sites constructing `StageInvocation` need updating.\n\n---\n\n### Option B \u2014 Compute ceiling from `invocation.MaxTurns` in `RunAsync`, with config override\n\n**Keep the default as 0** (meaning \"compute from turns\"). **In `RunAsync`**, if `_config.SubagentTimeoutMilliseconds` is 0, compute ceiling = `invocation.MaxTurns * PerTurnEstimateMs` (e.g. 60 s per turn). Since `MaxTurns` is already the boosted value (set in `BuildInvocation`), the 10\u00d7 scaling is automatic. If the config explicitly sets `subagentTimeoutMs` > 0, use that value directly (no boost multiplication \u2014 the repo admin is responsible for setting it high enough for boosted tasks). **Optionally**, add a `TurnBoostMultiplier` to `StageInvocation` (default 1) so `RunAsync` can apply it even to an explicit config value.\n\n**Files touched:** `ProcessRunners.RunAsync.cs`, maybe `StageInvocation.cs` (optional), test files.\n\n**Pros:** No new config field in `RelayConfig`; no change to `RelayDriver.BuildInvocation`; `MaxTurns` already carries the boost information; minimal surface area.\n\n**Cons:** A config value explicitly set by the repo admin (e.g. 20 min) would NOT be multiplied, creating a silent trap for boosted tasks unless the optional multiplier field is added; the per-turn estimate is a magic constant buried in `RunAsync`.\n\n---\n\n### Option C \u2014 Derive ceiling from `MaxTurns` at config-construction time, apply boost in `BuildInvocation`\n\n**In `RelayConfigLoader.Defaults()`**, compute a derived `EffectiveSubagentTimeoutMs` from `MaxTurns * 60_000` (non-zero). **Add a `TurnBoostMultiplier` property** to `RelayConfig` (default 1). **In `BuildInvocation`**, when the task is boosted, set the effective ceiling on a new `StageInvocation` field = `config.EffectiveSubagentTimeoutMs * TurnBoostMultiplier`. **In `RunAsync`**, use the invocation's ceiling.\n\n**Files touched:** `RelayConfigLoader.cs`, `RelayConfig.cs`, `StageInvocation.cs`, `RelayDriver.VerifyFix.cs`, `ProcessRunners.RunAsync.cs`, test files.\n\n**Pros:** Config-construction is the natural place to turn a \"0 = unset\" into a real value; the multiplier is a first-class config concept; testable at the config level.\n\n**Cons:** More surface area than Option B; still needs the `StageInvocation` field.\n\n---\n\n```json\n{\n  \"summary\": \"The SubagentTimeoutMilliseconds defaults to 0 (disabled) in RelayConfigLoader, so every stage attempt lacks a hard absolute ceiling \u2014 a CPU-active but flailing agent can run unbounded. The fix must (a) set a non-zero default ceiling, (b) scale it by the 10\u00d7 TurnBoostMultiplier for tasks in BoostTurnsTaskIds, and (c) avoid any trace-event heuristic that would false-positive on long legitimate tool calls. Three approaches differ in where the ceiling is computed and how boost awareness is threaded into RunAsync.\",\n  \"options\": [\n    \"Option A \u2014 Thread scaled ceiling through a new StageInvocation.AbsoluteCeilingMs field: change config default to non-zero, apply boost in BuildInvocation (co-located with turn boost), consume in RunAsync. Explicit, testable, but touches the domain record.\",\n    \"Option B \u2014 Compute ceiling from invocation.MaxTurns in RunAsync when config is 0: leverages the already-boosted MaxTurns for automatic scaling. Minimal surface area, but a repo-explicit config value bypasses boost scaling unless an optional multiplier is also added to StageInvocation.\",\n    \"Option C \u2014 Derive ceiling from MaxTurns at config-construction time (RelayConfigLoader), add TurnBoostMultiplier to RelayConfig, apply in BuildInvocation. Natural place to turn 0\u2192real value; multiplier becomes first-class config concept; more surface area than Option B.\"\n  ]\n}\n```",
